114
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:15,690
We're at 10.5 degrees.

115
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:16,921
FEMALE <i>AUTOMATED</i> VOICE:
<i>Warning. Excessive tilt.</i>

116
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,810
Tilting to 11
with all the gusts of wind.

117
00:06:20,080 --> 00:06:21,320
Copy that.

118
00:06:21,520 --> 00:06:23,887
Everyone, hone in
on Martinez's suit.

119
00:06:24,040 --> 00:06:26,088
It'll get you to airlock.
Get in, prep for launch.

120
00:06:26,400 --> 00:06:27,765
BECK: What about you,
Commander?

121
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:30,605
I'm gonna search
a little longer. Get moving!

122
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:31,921
Go!

123
00:06:35,680 --> 00:06:36,806
Watney!

124
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:38,964
Watney, report!

125
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:41,168
MARTINEZ: <i>The MA V's
at 11. 6 degrees.</i>

126
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:43,211
One good gust
and we're tipping.

127
00:06:43,360 --> 00:06:44,566
If it tips, you launch.

128
00:06:44,720 --> 00:06:46,085
You really think
I'm gonna leave you behind?

129
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:47,810
LEWIS: That's an order,
Martinez.

130
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:50,443
Mark!
(BECK GRUNTING)

131
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:53,769
Mark! Can you hear me?

132
00:06:55,280 --> 00:06:58,045
Martinez, what about
the proximity radar?

133
00:06:58,200 --> 00:06:59,884
Could that detect
Watney's suit?

134
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:01,371
MARTINEZ: It's made to see
the Hermes from orbit...

135
00:07:01,560 --> 00:07:03,449
not a little piece of metal
from a single suit.

136
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:04,601
LEWIS: <i>Give it</i> a <i>try.</i>

137
00:07:04,680 --> 00:07:05,681
MARTINEZ: Roger.

138
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:06,921
VOGEL: What is she thinking?
She knows

139
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:08,126
the infrared can't
get through a sandstorm.

140
00:07:08,320 --> 00:07:10,448
BECK: She's grasping
for anything.

141
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:11,601
<i>MARTINEZ: We've got
negative contact</i>

142
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:12,761
<i>on the proximity radar.</i>

143
00:07:12,880 --> 00:07:13,881
LEWIS: Nothing?

144
00:07:14,040 --> 00:07:16,008
<i>MARTINEZ: No.
I can barely see the Hab.</i>

145
00:07:17,160 --> 00:07:19,288
Commander, I know you don't
wanna hear this, but...

146
00:07:19,440 --> 00:07:20,521
Mark is dead.

147
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:23,371
<i>Commander!</i>

148
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:26,046
Hey, what the hell
is wrong with you, man?

149
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:27,201
My friend just died.

150
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,486
I don't want
my commander to die, too.

151
00:07:28,640 --> 00:07:29,880
FEMALE <i>AUTOMATED</i> VOICE:
<i>Stability warning.</i>

152
00:07:30,080 --> 00:07:31,127
We're tipping!

153
00:07:31,280 --> 00:07:34,568
BECK: <i>Commander, you need
to get back to the ship, now!</i>

154
00:07:34,680 --> 00:07:35,681
MARTINEZ: 13 degrees.

155
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:38,130
If we pass balance,
we'll never rock back.

156
00:07:38,280 --> 00:07:39,520
MARTINEZ: I've got
one more trick left,

157
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:41,045
and then I'm following orders,
Commander.

158
00:07:42,920 --> 00:07:44,410
You're firing the OMS?
(ALARM BEEPING)

159
00:07:45,040 --> 00:07:46,041
That's right.

160
00:07:50,080 --> 00:07:51,161
Commander!

161
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:53,046
LEWIS: On my way.
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

162
00:07:56,440 --> 00:07:57,646
<i>MARTINEZ: Johanssen, let's go.</i>

163
00:07:57,720 --> 00:07:58,846
(SIGHS)

164
00:08:01,200 --> 00:08:02,611
(STRUGGLING)

165
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:07,248
LEWIS: Mark!

166
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:20,850
MARTINEZ: <i>We're at 11.5
and holding.</i>

167
00:08:24,560 --> 00:08:25,607
<i>Ready to go on your command.</i>

168
00:08:28,040 --> 00:08:29,121
Ready to launch.

169
00:08:30,400 --> 00:08:31,640
Commander.

170
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:33,644
I need you to verbally tell me
whether or not to.

171
00:08:33,800 --> 00:08:34,881
Launch.

172
00:09:16,480 --> 00:09:18,084
SANDERS ON TV:
At around 4:30 a.m.

173
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:19,645
<i>Central Standard Time...</i>

174
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:21,882
<i>our satellites
detected a storm</i>

175
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:24,486
<i>approaching the Ares 3
mission site on Mars.</i>

176
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:28,487
<i>At 6:45, the storm
had escalated to severe...</i>

177
00:09:28,640 --> 00:09:31,530
<i>and we had no choice
but to abort the mission.</i>

178
00:09:31,680 --> 00:09:34,081
<i>Thanks to the quick action
of Commander Lewis...</i>

179
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:37,369
<i>astronauts Beck, Johanssen,
Martinez and Vogel...</i>

180
00:09:37,520 --> 00:09:40,251
<i>were all able to reach
the Mars Ascent Vehicle...</i>

181
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:43,847
<i>and perform an emergency
launch at 7:28 Central Time.</i>

182
00:09:45,400 --> 00:09:47,607
Unfortunately,
during the evacuation...

183
00:09:47,760 --> 00:09:51,765
