01:52:45,360 --> 01:52:47,203
<i>as to what exactly
is going on.</i>

1697
01:52:47,400 --> 01:52:51,041
<i>Let's listen in to NASA making
contact with Mark Watney.</i>

1698
01:52:51,240 --> 01:52:52,446
<i>Let's listen in.</i>

1699
01:52:59,120 --> 01:53:01,407
If something goes wrong,
what can Mission Control do?

1700
01:53:01,840 --> 01:53:03,968
Not a damn thing.

1701
01:53:04,480 --> 01:53:06,289
It's all happening
12 light-minutes away...

1702
01:53:06,440 --> 01:53:08,124
which means it takes
24 minutes for them

1703
01:53:08,200 --> 01:53:10,168
to get the answer to any
question they ask.

1704
01:53:11,280 --> 01:53:13,328
The whole launch
is 12 minutes...

1705
01:53:15,040 --> 01:53:16,690
so they're on their own.

1706
01:53:21,360 --> 01:53:22,691
(russme IN PAIN)

1707
01:53:34,200 --> 01:53:35,565
(WHIRRING)

1708
01:54:11,920 --> 01:54:13,888
(WOMAN SPEAKING
MANDARIN ON PA)

1709
01:54:21,880 --> 01:54:22,881
<i>REPORTER: ...just how long
Mark has been</i>

1710
01:54:23,000 --> 01:54:24,081
<i>completely alone on Mars.</i>

1711
01:54:24,160 --> 01:54:27,130
<i>We're talking to a psychology
expert later to discuss...</i>

1712
01:54:49,880 --> 01:54:51,484
J O <i>HAN</i> S S E <i>N: Fuel pressure,
green.</i>

1713
01:54:51,840 --> 01:54:54,002
Engine alignment, perfect.

1714
01:54:54,160 --> 01:54:55,446
<i>Communications, five by five.</i>

1715
01:54:57,200 --> 01:54:59,965
<i>We are ready for pre-ﬂight
checklist, Commander.</i>

1716
01:55:00,160 --> 01:55:02,731
LEWIS: <i>Mission Control,
this is Hermes actual.</i>

1717
01:55:02,800 --> 01:55:04,802
<i>We will proceed on schedule.</i>

1718
01:55:05,000 --> 01:55:07,002
<i>We are T-minus 2 minutes,
10 seconds</i>

1719
01:55:07,080 --> 01:55:08,491
<i>to launch, by the mark.</i>

1720
01:55:09,720 --> 01:55:10,721
About two minutes, Watney.

1721
01:55:10,920 --> 01:55:12,001
<i>How you doing down there?</i>

1722
01:55:12,160 --> 01:55:13,366
I'm good.

1723
01:55:14,200 --> 01:55:16,009
I'm anxious to get up to you.

1724
01:55:16,520 --> 01:55:17,885
Thanks for coming back for me.

1725
01:55:17,960 --> 01:55:18,961
<i>LEWIS: Well, we're on it.</i>

1726
01:55:19,120 --> 01:55:20,849
<i>Remember, you'll be pulling
some serious G's,</i>

1727
01:55:20,920 --> 01:55:22,604
<i>so it's okay to pass out.</i>

1728
01:55:22,760 --> 01:55:24,728
You're in
Martinez's hands now.

1729
01:55:25,400 --> 01:55:27,482
Well, tell that asshole
no barrel rolls.

1730
01:55:27,560 --> 01:55:28,561
(LAUGHS)

1731
01:55:28,920 --> 01:55:30,206
Copy that, MAV.

1732
01:55:30,680 --> 01:55:31,681
<i>CAPCOM.</i>

1733
01:55:31,800 --> 01:55:32,767
JOHANSSENI Go.

1734
01:55:32,840 --> 01:55:33,887
LEWIS: Remote command.
(C RYING)

1735
01:55:33,960 --> 01:55:34,927
MARTINEZ: Go.

1736
01:55:35,000 --> 01:55:36,001
<i>LEWIS: Recovery.</i>

1737
01:55:36,080 --> 01:55:37,081
BECK: Go.

1738
01:55:37,200 --> 01:55:38,611
<i>LEWIS: Secondary recovery.</i>

1739
01:55:38,680 --> 01:55:39,681
VOGEL: Go-.

1740
01:55:39,800 --> 01:55:40,801
Pilot.

1741
01:55:42,160 --> 01:55:43,161
Go.

1742
01:55:43,280 --> 01:55:44,486
<i>LEWIS: Pilot.</i>

1743
01:55:44,640 --> 01:55:45,766
WATNEYI Go.
(ALL CHEERING)

1744
01:55:45,920 --> 01:55:46,967
MISSION CONTROL TECHNICIAN:
<i>Copy.</i> We're go.

1745
01:55:48,120 --> 01:55:50,487
LEWIS: <i>Mission Control,
we are go for launch.</i>

1746
01:55:51,320 --> 01:55:52,526
T-minus ten...

1747
01:55:52,640 --> 01:55:53,607
nine...

1748
01:55:53,680 --> 01:55:54,681
Main engine start.

1749
01:55:54,880 --> 01:55:56,006
<i>JOHANSSEN". eight...</i>

1750
01:55:56,360 --> 01:55:57,361
<i>SGVGH...</i>

1751
01:55:57,520 --> 01:55:59,170
<i>Mooring clamps released.</i>

1752
01:55:59,320 --> 01:56:00,924
About five seconds, Watney.
Hang on.

1753
01:56:01,080 --> 01:56:02,764
I'll see you in a few,
Commander.

1754
01:56:03,040 --> 01:56:04,371
JOHANSSEN: four...

1755
01:56:04,760 --> 01:56:06,046
<i>three...</i>

1756
01:56:06,320 --> 01:56:07,526
<i>two...</i>

1757
01:56:07,920 --> 01:56:08,967
<i>one.</i>

1758
01:56:16,560 --> 01:56:17,686
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1759
01:56:45,240 --> 01:56:47,641
JOHANSSEN: Velocity,
741 meters per second.

1760
01:56:47,800 --> 01:56:49,768
Altitude, 1350 meters.

1761
01:56:49,920 --> 01:56:51,081
That's too low.

1762
01:56:51,240 --> 01:56:52,401
It's fighting me.

1763
01:56:56,240 --> 01:56:59,483
<i>LEWIS: (ECHOING)
Watney, do you read?</i>

1764
01:56:59,560 --> 01:57:01,403
(GROANING SOFTLY)

1765
01:57:05,480 --> 01:57:06,766
<i>MARTINEZ: Booster
separation complete.</i>

1766
01:57:06,920 --> 01:57:09,969
Velocity, 850.
Altitude, 1843.

1767
01:57:10,160 --> 01:57:11,366
He's well below
target altitude.

1768
01:57:11,520 --> 01:57:12,760
How far below?

1769
01:57:13,280 --> 01:57:14,361
JOHANSSEN: Checking.

1770
01:57:14,960 --> 01:57:16,166
Watney.

1771
01:57:16,800 --> 01:57:17,801
Do you read?

1772
01:57:18,080 --> 01:57:19,286
BECK: <i>He's probably
passed out.</i>

1773
01:57:19,440 --> 01:57:20,601
<i>He pulled 12 g's
on the ascent.</i>

1774
01:57:20,720 --> 01:57:21,960
<i>Give him a few minutes.</i>

1775
01:57:22,120 --> 01:57:23,281
LEWIS: Copy that.

1776
01:57:25,640 --> 01:57:26,971
<i>JOHANSSEN: Main shutdown
in three...</i>

1777
01:57:27,640 --> 01:57:29,210
two, one...

1778
01:57:29,920 --> 01:57:31,001
<i>shutdown.</i>

1779
01:57:32,560 --> 01:57:34,050
MARTINEZ: <i>Back to
automatic guidance.</i>

1780
01:57:35,000 --> 01:57:36,365
<i>Shutdown confirmed.</i>

1781
01:57:38,840 --> 01:57:40,604
<i>Fuel reserves depleted.</i>

1782
01:57:42,520 --> 01:57:43,681
<i>LEWIS: Watney?</i>

1783
01:57:44,280 --> 01:57:45,486
<i>Do you read?</i>

1784
01:57:46,480 --> 01:57:47,686
<i>It seems there's some
sort of problem</i>

1785
01:57:47,760 --> 01:57:49,171
<i>with the transmission.</i>

1786
01:57:56,320 --> 01:57:57,890
<i>JOHANSSEN:
I have interval pings.</i>

1787
01:57:58,040 --> 01:58:00,088
Intercept velocity will be
11 meters per second.

1788
01:58:00,240 --> 01:58:02,004
I can make that work.

1789
01:58:02,600 --> 01:58:04,967
JOHANSSEN: Distance
at intercept will be...

1790
01:58:05,400 --> 01:58:07,084
We'll be 68 kilometers apart.

1791
01:58:07,520 --> 01:58:09,329
<i>BECK". 68 kilometers?</i>

1792
01:58:09,560 --> 01:58:12,006
<i>Did she just say
68 kilometers?</i>

1793
01:58:12,760 --> 01:58:13,761
Come on, guys,
keep it together.

1794
01:58:13,840 --> 01:58:14,887
Work the problem.

1795
01:58:15,560 --> 01:58:17,164
Johanssen, time to intercept?

1796
01:58:17,840 --> 01:58:19,842
<i>JOHANSSEN: 39 minutes,
12 seconds.</i>

1797
01:58:20,520 --> 01:58:22,010
Martinez, what if we
point our thrusters

1798
01:58:22,080 --> 01:58:23,241
in the same direction?

1799
01:58:23,680 --> 01:58:26,650
Well, it depends how much fuel
you wanna save...

1800
01:58:26,800 --> 01:58:28,165
for the altitude adjustments
for the trip home.

1801
01:58:28,320 --> 01:58:29,401
How much do you need?

1802
01:58:29,560 --> 01:58:33,849
I can get by with about 20%
of what we have left.

1803
01:58:34,920 --> 01:58:38,163
If we use 75.5% of remaining
altitude-adjust fuel...

1804
01:58:38,320 --> 01:58:40,209
that will bring the intercept
range to zero.

1805
01:58:40,320 --> 01:58:41,321
Do it.

1806
01:58:42,240 --> 01:58:45,369
Hang on. It brings
the range to zero...

1807
01:58:45,520 --> 01:58:48,251
but the intercept velocity
will be 42 meters per second.

1808
01:58:48,400 --> 01:58:50,050
<i>And that's way too fast.</i>

1809
01:58:50,440 --> 01:58:52,442
Then we'll have 39 minutes
to figure out

1810
01:58:52,560 --> 01:58:54,085
how to slow down.

1811
01:58:57,160 --> 01:58:58,924
Martinez, burn the jets.

1812
01:58:59,080 --> 01:59:00,491
MARTINEZ: Copy that.

1813
01:59:22,920 --> 01:59:24,968
<i>MAV</i> to <i>Hermes.</i>

1814
01:59:25,040 --> 01:59:26,041
<i>LEWIS: Watney?</i>

1815
01:59:26,160 --> 01:59:27,161
<i>WATNEY'. Affirmative.</i>

1816
01:59:27,240 --> 01:59:28,241
(ALL CHEERING)

1817
01:59:31,200 --> 01:59:32,645
<i>LEWIS: What's your status?</i>

1818
01:59:33,000 --> 01:59:34,525
<i>WATNEY". My chest hurts.</i>

1819
01:59:35,040 --> 01:59:36,405
<i>I broke my ribs.</i>

1820
01:59:37,240 --> 01:59:38,321
<i>How are you?</i>

1821
01:59:38,520 --> 01:59:39,601
<i>LEWIS: We're working on
getting to you.</i>

1822
01:59:39,680 --> 01:59:41,170
<i>There was a complication
during launch.</i>

1823
01:59:41,360 --> 01:59:42,725
Copy that.

1824
01:59:43,280 --> 01:59:44,725
How bad is it?

1825
01:59:44,880 --> 01:59:46,450
LEWIS: <i>We've corrected
the intercept range,</i>

1826
01:59:46,520 --> 01:59:48,488
<i>but we've got a problem
with intercept velocity.</i>

1827
01:59:48,640 --> 01:59:49,926
<i>WATNEY". How big a problem?</i>

1828
01:59:50,120 --> 01:59:51,610
42 meters a second.

1829
01:59:51,960 --> 01:59:52,961
Well...

1830
01:59:54,280 --> 01:59:55,725
Shit.

1831
02:00:00,640 --> 02:00:02,449
<i>Commander, I have an idea.</i>

1832
02:00:02,600 --> 02:00:04,045
LEWIS: Go ahead, Mark.

1833
02:00:04,200 --> 02:00:07,363
Well, if I can find
something sharp in here...

1834
02:00:07,520 --> 02:00:10,364
and poke a hole in the glove
of my EVA suit...

1835
02:00:10,520 --> 02:00:13,000
I could use the escaping air
as a thruster...

1836
02:00:13,160 --> 02:00:14,571
<i>and fly towards you.</i>

1837
02:00:14,720 --> 02:00:17,769
<i>It would be easy to control
because it would be on my arm.</i>

1838
02:00:18,040 --> 02:00:19,883
LEWIS: I can't see you having
any control if you did that.

1839
02:00:20,040 --> 02:00:21,849
You'd be eyeballing
the intercept

1840
02:00:21,920 --> 02:00:24,207
using a thrust vector
you can barely control.

1841
02:00:24,440 --> 02:00:27,603
Yes, those are all
very good points.

1842
02:00:28,400 --> 02:00:31,165
But consider this.

1843
02:00:33,200 --> 02:00:35,851
I'd get to fly around
like Iron Man.

1844
02:00:36,040 --> 02:00:37,087
(JOHANSSEN LAUGHS)

1845
02:00:37,160 --> 02:00:38,730
WATNEY: Commander...

1846
02:00:38,880 --> 02:00:40,564
<i>let's go Iron Man.</i>

1847
02:00:43,640 --> 02:00:44,926
NASA TECHNICIAN 1:
This <i>is</i> unexpected LOS.

1848
02:00:45,160 --> 02:00:47,049
NASA <i>TECHNICIAN 2:
Communication lost. Stand by.</i>

1849
02:00:48,080 --> 02:00:50,731
Maybe it's not the worst idea.

1850
02:00:50,880 --> 02:00:52,723
No, it is the worst idea.
It's the worst idea ever.

1851
02:00:52,880 --> 02:00:54,006
Not what he said.

1852
02:00:54,160 --> 02:00:56,288
Using atmosphere as thrust.

1853
02:00:58,520 --> 02:01:00,443
What happens
if we blow the VAL?

1854
02:01:00,720 --> 02:01:02,529
Wait, you want to open
the vehicular airlock?

1855
02:01:02,760 --> 02:01:03,841
It'll give us a good kick.

1856
02:01:04,000 --> 02:01:05,764
But also blow
the nose off the ship.

1857
02:01:05,920 --> 02:01:08,730
And all the air would leave
and we need air to not die.

1858
02:01:08,880 --> 02:01:11,121
We would seal the bridge
and the reactor room.

1859
02:01:11,320 --> 02:01:12,560
Everywhere else
would go vacuo.

1860
02:01:13,200 --> 02:01:14,201
Vogel.

1861
02:01:14,280 --> 02:01:15,566
VOGEL: Go ahead, Commander.

1862
02:01:15,960 --> 02:01:18,611
I need you to come inside
and make a... bomb.

1863
02:01:19,360 --> 02:01:20,327
Again, Commander?

1864
02:01:20,400 --> 02:01:21,401
LEWIS: <i>You're</i> a <i>chemist.</i>

1865
02:01:21,480 --> 02:01:23,323
<i>Can you make a bomb with
what you have on board?</i>

1866
02:01:25,000 --> 02:01:26,286
Probably.

1867
02:01:27,360 --> 02:01:28,646
But I feel obliged to mention

1868
02:01:28,760 --> 02:01:30,524
that setting off
an explosive device...

1869
02:01:30,720 --> 02:01:33,451
<i>in a spacecraft
is a terrible, terrible idea.</i>

1870
02:01:33,800 --> 02:01:36,690
Hang on. You guys making
a bomb without me?

1871
02:01:36,840 --> 02:01:38,842
LEWIS: <i>Copy that.
Can you do it?</i>

1872
02:01:41,240 --> 02:01:42,241
Ja.

1873
02:01:45,160 --> 02:01:46,764
<i>LEWIS: Houston, be advised.</i>

1874
02:01:46,920 --> 02:01:48,410
<i>We are going to deliberately
breach the VAL</i>

1875
02:01:48,480 --> 02:01:50,005
<i>to produce a reverse thrust.</i>

1876
02:01:51,240 --> 02:01:53,641
Beck, leave your suit on.
Meet Johanssen in Airlock 1.

1877
02:01:53,800 --> 02:01:54,847
We'll open the outer door.

1878
02:01:55,000 --> 02:01:56,684
<i>I need you to place the charge
on the inner door.</i>

1879
02:01:57,160 --> 02:01:59,288
<i>Climb back to Airlock 2
along the hull.</i>

1880
02:01:59,440 --> 02:02:01,283
BECK: Copy. I'm on my way.

1881
02:02:08,520 --> 02:02:10,010
I'm in, Commander.

1882
02:02:10,160 --> 02:02:11,207
LEWIS: Copy that.

1883
02:02:20,360 --> 02:02:21,964
Vogel, where are you?

1884
02:02:22,120 --> 02:02:23,167
<i>VOGEL". I'm in the kitchen.</i>

1885
02:02:23,320 --> 02:02:24,321
Okay-

1886
02:02:28,360 --> 02:02:29,361
WATNEY: Commander...

1887
02:02:29,520 --> 02:02:31,409
I can't let you
go through with this.

1888
02:02:31,560 --> 02:02:33,130
I am prepared to cut the suit.

1889
02:02:33,440 --> 02:02:34,487
Absolutely not.

1890
02:02:34,640 --> 02:02:37,041
<i>WATNEY: See, the thing is,
I'm selfish.</i>

1891
02:02:37,280 --> 02:02:40,170
I want all the memorials back
home to be about me.

1892
02:02:40,240 --> 02:02:41,241
<i>Just me.</i>

1893
02:02:41,360 --> 02:02:43,647
I should have left
this guy on Mars.

1894
02:02:43,960 --> 02:02:45,007
Hey-

1895
02:02:47,880 --> 02:02:48,881
Sugar?

1896
02:02:48,960 --> 02:02:49,961
Yeah.

1897
02:02:54,080 --> 02:02:55,491
Can you hold this?

1898
02:02:56,080 --> 02:02:57,809
Liquid oxygen...

1899
02:02:57,960 --> 02:03:01,442
and some stain remover
that contains ammonia.

1900
02:03:04,960 --> 02:03:08,248
This thing here
is five times stronger

1901
02:03:08,320 --> 02:03:09,765
than a stick of dynamite.

1902
02:03:09,840 --> 02:03:11,080
How do we activate it?

1903
02:03:11,240 --> 02:03:14,005
Can you connect this to
one of our lighting panels?

1904
02:03:17,560 --> 02:03:18,846
Careful.

1905
02:03:25,400 --> 02:03:26,925
BECK: Open Airlock 1.

1906
02:03:32,720 --> 02:03:33,960
JOHANSSEN: I'm on
the way to Beck.

1907
02:03:38,200 --> 02:03:40,089
Let's just hope
this is a good idea, guys.

1908
02:03:40,160 --> 02:03:41,207
It is.

1909
02:03:41,280 --> 02:03:42,486
<i>JOHANSSEN". Open A1.</i>

1910
02:03:47,840 --> 02:03:48,841
Hi.
Hey.

1911
02:03:52,520 --> 02:03:54,045
You got it?
Mmm.

1912
02:03:59,680 --> 02:04:02,331
Make sure you're not in here
when this thing goes off.

1913
02:04:04,120 --> 02:04:05,326
Hey-

1914
02:04:05,480 --> 02:04:07,323
Be careful out there.

1915
02:04:07,480 --> 02:04:08,641
In space.

1916
02:04:12,720 --> 02:04:15,121
Don't tell anyone
I did that.

1917
02:04:25,000 --> 02:04:26,047
Bomb set.
(BEEPING)

1918
02:04:34,800 --> 02:04:37,167
Leaving Airlock 1.

1919
02:04:42,120 --> 02:04:43,246
MARTINEZ: Guys,
I'm running the numbers,

1920
02:04:43,320 --> 02:04:44,481
and even with
optimal VAL blow...

1921
02:04:44,760 --> 02:04:46,330
we're gonna be off
on our angle.

1922
02:04:46,640 --> 02:04:49,325
What's the intercept
distance? Johanssen?

1923
02:04:49,480 --> 02:04:51,801
260 meters, approximate.

1924
02:04:52,000 --> 02:04:53,286
That's too far.

1925
02:04:57,600 --> 02:04:58,601
(GROANS)

1926
02:05:02,320 --> 02:05:03,606
Commander?

1927
02:05:03,760 --> 02:05:05,649
Martinez, close the door.

1928
02:05:09,120 --> 02:05:10,451
Open D3.

1929
02:05:10,960 --> 02:05:12,803
And leave it open.

1930
02:05:40,240 --> 02:05:41,401
(GROANS)

1931
02:05:41,480 --> 02:05:43,164
<i>Open B2.</i>

1932
02:05:47,360 --> 02:05:48,600
Johanssen“.

1933
02:05:48,760 --> 02:05:51,081
<i>Time to VAL blow
after initiate?</i>

1934
02:05:51,240 --> 02:05:52,446
15 seconds.

1935
02:05:52,680 --> 02:05:54,728
We sure know
how to cut it close.

1936
02:05:55,640 --> 02:05:56,687
Commander?

1937
02:05:56,760 --> 02:05:58,728
Distance is too far.
I'm going out.

1938
02:05:59,320 --> 02:06:00,321
I can do this.

1939
